<header>
    <h1>WFH CODE</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Remote Discipline Guide for BPO Professionals</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

<div class="card">

<p>
Working from home in BPO sounds like freedom until you realize freedom still has KPIs and someone, somewhere, is timing your bathroom breaks in spirit.
</p>

<p>
Here's what actually matters, beyond the usual "get a headset and a quiet room" advice everyone recycles like it's sacred knowledge.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">1. Your real enemy is micro-distraction stacking</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>People blame Facebook, games, or noise.</p>

<p>Wrong target.</p>

<p>What actually kills performance:</p>

<ul>
<li>10 seconds checking phone</li>
<li>20 seconds switching tabs</li>
<li>5 seconds thinking about something else</li>
<li>Repeating this hundreds of times per day</li>
</ul>

<p>
Individually harmless. Collectively fatal.
</p>

<p>
WFH success is basically how few times you switch mental states per hour.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">2. Invisible accountability beats self-discipline tricks</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
Motivation apps? Planners? Pomodoro timers?
</p>

<p>
Cute.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Keep your screen work-visible</li>
<li>Remove neutral tabs</li>
<li>Start work immediately after login</li>
</ul>

<p>
The trick is removing decisions, not improving willpower.
</p>

<p>
Willpower is unreliable. Systems are not.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">3. Your chair position affects your QA score</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
Bad posture quietly creates:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Subtle fatigue</li>
<li>Slower response time</li>
<li>Micro-errors in judgment</li>
<li>More procrastinated fixes</li>
</ul>

<p>
WFH performance often starts declining in the spine before it appears in QA.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">4. Transition friction is the silent productivity killer</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
Every time you:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Go to lunch</li>
<li>Check your phone</li>
<li>Step away for a break</li>
</ul>

<p>
Your brain pays a restart tax.
</p>

<p>
The skill isn't working fast. It's returning to focus quickly.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">5. Your headset is a performance instrument</h2>

<div class="card">

<ul>
<li>Audio clarity affects confidence</li>
<li>Delay creates conversational panic</li>
<li>Poor mic quality increases repetition errors</li>
</ul>

<p>
A bad headset doesn't just sound bad. It creates stress loops.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">6. Queue fear control</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
People don't slow down because tasks are hard.
</p>

<p>
They slow down because they fear mistakes.
</p>

<p>
Over-checking often hurts productivity more than actual errors.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">7. Back office auto-skip syndrome</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
After enough repetition, your brain starts:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Skipping verification steps</li>
<li>Assuming correctness</li>
<li>Rushing confirmations</li>
</ul>

<p>
This is how silent errors accumulate.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">8. The invisible fatigue curve</h2>

<div class="card">

<ul>
<li>Slightly slower</li>
<li>Slightly less careful</li>
<li>Slightly more forgetful</li>
</ul>

<p>
That "slightly" is what destroys accuracy scores.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">9. Breaks are reset protocols</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
Treat breaks like system resets, not entertainment sessions.
</p>

<p>
The quality of your return matters more than the length of your break.
</p>

</div>

<h2 class="section-title">10. Context switching without emotional residue</h2>

<div class="card">

<p>
Can you:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Handle a difficult interaction</li>
<li>Log it correctly</li>
<li>Move immediately to the next task</li>
<li>Leave frustration behind</li>
</ul>

<p>
Most burnout begins when emotions travel from task to task.
</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h2>Final Truth</h2>

<p>
WFH success in BPO is not about comfort.
</p>

<p>
It is about controlling:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Distraction leakage</li>
<li>Mental resets</li>
<li>Repetition fatigue</li>
<li>Emotional carryover</li>
</ul>

<p>
People think working from home gives freedom.
</p>

<p>
It actually gives exposure.
</p>

<p>
You see exactly how disciplined your attention really is.
</p>

